    <h3>
      The Ariosto Ensemble</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>General Information</strong><br />
      The <i><strong>Ariosto Ensemble</strong></i>, performing since 2002, is a project ensemble, varying its membership per projected
      programme. Singers and instrumentalists are specifically selected for each particular concert programme. Whether the ensemble
      presents itself as consisting of professional musicians or of high-quality amateurs partly depends on the theme and nature
      of the music to be performed.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Name</strong><br />
      The name <i><strong>Ariosto Ensemble</strong></i> derives from Ludovico Ariosto (1474-1533), an Italian epicist and lyricist,
      a favourite with the ducal d'Este family, holding court at Ferrara and renowned at the time. His famous epic entitled <i><strong>
        Orlando Furioso</strong></i> prompted numerous Renaissance and Baroque composers to use (parts, cantos of) this work as
      a source of inspiration for their compositions. In 2002 the <i><strong>Ariosto Ensemble</strong></i> put a madrigal drama
      entitled "<i><strong>Orlando Furioso</strong></i>" on stage, comprising compositions by di Lasso, Palestrina, de Wert, de
      Monte, Ruffo and others. This successful programme, with 12 performances throughout the Netherlands and a wireless recording
      in the shape of a documentary, broadcast by the VPRO, formed the starting-point for setting up more projects.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Membership</strong><br />
      In order to participate, members of the ensemble have to meet certain requirements. For professional projects, the musicians
      are recruited by the artistic direction. For programmes allowing the participation of amateur musicians, it is possible
      to apply for selection. Auditions are held for the purpose. In very special cases, a comprehensive c.v. may suffice. For
      (amateur) singers, the ability to sing a part of a four- or five-part madrigal or motet independently is a minimum requirement.
      Frequent use is made of the original notation - being acquainted with or willing to learn this notation is indispensable.
      Possessing a well-trained voice is a prerequisite, and having to sing in languages like English, Italian, (Old-)French and
      various linguistic forms of Latin should not form a stumbling-block.<br />
      <a href="contact.asp">To apply, please click here</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Projects carried out</strong><br />
      Besides the &quot;Orlando Furioso&quot; project mentioned above, the ensemble carried out projects entitled &quot;Shakespeare
      in love&quot;, &quot;I begl' occhi&quot; (3 performances of which took place in France) and &quot;Around 1500&quot; (with
      a number of performances in the Netherlands and abroad still to come in 2009).
    </p>
